n moral order. Focussing on the Terapanthi moral universe from the perspective of female renouncers, Vallely considers how Terapanthi Jain women create their own ascetic subjectivities, and how they construct and understand themselves as symbols of renunciation. The first in-depth ethnographic study of this important and influential Jain tradition, this work makes a significant contribution to Jain studies, comparative religion, Indian studies, and the anthropology of South Asian religion.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aAsceticismxJainism. 0aAsceticsxIndiaxLadnun. 0aAsceticszIndiazLadnun. 0aAscètesxIndexLadnun. 0aAscétismexJaïnisme. 0aEthnologiexAspect religieuxxJaïnismexRajasthanxTerapanthxIndiaxLadnun. 0aEthnologyxIndiaxLadnun. 0aEthnologyxReligious aspectsxJainism. 0aEthnologyzIndiazLadnun. 0aJaina womenxIndiaxLadnun. 0aJaina womenzIndiazLadnun. 0aTerehpanth (Jaina sect) 0aTerehpanth (Jaina sect). 0aTerâpanthî (Secte jaïna). 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267554440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442675544423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442675544.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK